    <stitle>FRONT DRIVE AXLE WHEEL ENDS: ROCKWELL - LUBRICATION - LUBRICATION PROCEDURES</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="lubricate" graphiccount="2">
        <title>LUBRICATION PROCEDURES</title>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Steering Universal Joints:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Check to see that the parts not loose, but free enough to move.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Apply grease until new grease flows from all seals.</para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the grease does not flow from the seals, move the joint up and down until flowing
                    occurs.
                </para>
            </step2>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">If the grease still does not flow, check the condition of the grease in the universal
                    joint. If the grease appears dirty of burned, replace the complete joint assembly.
                </para>
            </step2>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Wheel Bearings:</para>
            <step2>
                <para count="1">Grease Lubricated (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0200840">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0200840" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200840.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Grease Lubricated Hub</caption>
                </figure>
                <step3>
                    <para>Before you install the wheel bearings on the spindle, apply a thin layer of grease to the
                        bearing journals to prevent corrosion.
                    </para>
                </step3>
                <step3>
                    <para>Use a pressure packer to lubricate the wheel bearings. If a pressure packer is not available,
                        fill the bearings by hand, forcing the lubricant in the cavities between the rollers and cage
                        from the large end of the bearing cone.
                    </para>
                </step3>
                <step3>
                    <para>Fill the hub between the two bearing cups with grease up to the smallest diameter of the cups
                        (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0200840">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                </step3>
                <step3>
                    <para>On axles with greasable drive flanges, pump the lube through the grease fitting until it
                        purges at the axle shaft seal (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0200841">Figure 41</hotlnk>).
                    </para>
                    <figure id="f0200841" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic filename="../figg02/G0200841.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 41. Pump Grease Through Grease Fittings</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. GREASE FITTING</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. SEAL</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step3>
            </step2>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
